gomodel:SYNGO_333  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Liu et.al. provides multiple lines of evidence that ELKS proteins control action potential-evoked calcium influx in inhibitory presynaptic terminals.\n\n-In presynaptic calcium imaging, ELKS DKO shows a reduction in AP-induced calcium entry (Figure 8).\n-ELKS DKO displays a reduction in AP-induced vesicle fusion as measured with electrophysiology (Figure 5). Release has a reduced sensitivity to Ca2+ (EC50) without affecting the cooperativity. This is in line with a defect in calcium entry, and not the calcium sensor of the release machinery.\n-There is no defect in the synaptic localization of calcium channels, as shown with immunocytochemistry (figure 9).\nTaken together, these data show that ELKS proteins control the opening of calcium channels.\n\nSince this study has been performed in ELKS1/2 double knockouts, the exact contribution of ELKS1 or ELKS2 is currently unknown.\n\n12/4/2017 Pim\n- These studies show that ELKS1 (in genetic interaction with ELKS2) regulate the activity of VGCC's in the presynapse.\n13/4/2017 Pim\n- Effect on SV release synapse type related. In inhibitory synapses (this annotation) ELKS influences SV release via an indirect mechanism, whereas in excitatory synapses ELKS regulates SV priming (see ticket #331).. Experimental description: Primary mouse hippocampal cultures from newborn pups were generated as previously described (Ho et al., 2006; Kaeser et al., 2008; Kaeser et al., 2009; Kaeser et al., 2011)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2018-06-07" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_333" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

